Title: Dracula
Credit: Written by
Author: Bram Stoker
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 3/20/2025
Notes: Period Victorian gothic live-action; fog, candlelight, cold stone, deep shadows. One continuous render medium for all humans and creatures. Count Dracula: tall, thin, aquiline nose, white hair and moustache at first meeting, cruel red mouth, pointed teeth, pale as wax, clad in black cloak and suit; later deathly still in his box of earth. Jonathan Harker: young English solicitor, neat brown hair, practical coat and travel clothes, later hardened, Kukri knife. Mina Harker: dark-haired, intelligent, modest Victorian dress, forehead once marked by curse then clear. Lucy Westenra: fair, beautiful, white gown in death. Dr. Seward: earnest young asylum physician, dark coat. Professor Van Helsing: older Dutch professor, sharp eyes, grey-streaked hair, foreign accent, black coat and hat. Quincey Morris: lean Texan, open face, bowie knife, practical kit. Lord Godalming (Arthur): grief-worn young nobleman, Winchester ready. Closed cast throughout.

===

EXT. EASTERN EUROPEAN COUNTRYSIDE - DAY

A steam train crawls through wild hills. Rivers with wide stony margins. Castles perch on steep heights like something from an old missal.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Left Munich at 8:35 P.M. on the first of May. Buda-Pesth seems a wonderful place—the impression was that we were leaving the West and entering the East.

INT. TRAIN COMPARTMENT - DAY

JONATHAN HARKER, young English solicitor in neat travel clothes, writes in a shorthand journal. Outside: peasants, Slovaks in big cowboy hats, baggy dirty-white trousers, brass-studded belts.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I had visited the British Museum regarding Transylvania. The district is in the extreme east, in the midst of the Carpathians—one of the wildest portions of Europe. Every known superstition is gathered into the horseshoe of the Carpathians, as if it were the centre of some imaginative whirlpool.

EXT. KLAUSENBURGH - NIGHT

Snow-dusted roofs. A dog howls under a window.

INT. HOTEL ROYALE - NIGHT

Harker eats paprika hendl by candlelight, drinks water thirstily. Queer dreams trouble his sleep.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I did not sleep well. There was a dog howling all night—or it may have been the paprika.

EXT. BISTRITZ - TWILIGHT

An old frontier town. Marks of fires and ancient siege. Harker walks with bag toward a timbered inn sign: GOLDEN KRONE.

INT. GOLDEN KRONE HOTEL - NIGHT

A cheery elderly LANDLADY in peasant dress—white undergarment, tight coloured double apron—bows at the door. An elderly LANDLORD in white shirt-sleeves hovers behind her.

LANDLADY
The Herr Englishman?

JONATHAN HARKER
Yes. Jonathan Harker.

She smiles, murmurs to the Landlord. He returns with a sealed letter. Harker breaks the seal and reads.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
“My Friend.—Welcome to the Carpathians. I am anxiously expecting you. Sleep well to-night. At three to-morrow the diligence will start for Bukovina; a place on it is kept for you. At the Borgo Pass my carriage will await you and will bring you to me. I trust that your journey from London has been a happy one, and that you will enjoy your stay in my beautiful land. Your friend, Dracula.”

Harker looks up, pleased. The Landlord and Landlady exchange a frightened glance.

JONATHAN HARKER
Do you know Count Dracula? Can you tell me anything of his castle?

The Landlord mumbles, pretends not to understand German he spoke perfectly a moment before. The Landlady crosses herself and turns away.

EXT. BISTRITZ COACH YARD - PRE-DAWN

Torches. A diligence waits. Locals hang back. Harker climbs aboard. The Landlady presses a small crucifix into his hand, eyes wet, then flees inside.

EXT. BORGO PASS - DAY TO DUSK

The coach rattles through dark pines, climbing. Wind rises. Other passengers glance at Harker and whisper. At a lonely crossroads the coach halts. A black calèche waits, driver muffled, horses stamping.

Harker alights. The diligence turns and flees as if pursued. The calèche door opens on darkness.

EXT. CASTLE DRACULA - NIGHT

A vast ruined pile on a precipice, broken battlements against a cold sky. The calèche rattles into a courtyard. Silence. No servants.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA - GREAT DOOR - NIGHT

Heavy doors open. COUNT DRACULA stands within—tall, thin, aquiline face, white hair and moustache, clad entirely in black. His hand is pale as ivory; his grip, when he takes Harker’s, is like ice and steel.

COUNT DRACULA
Welcome to my house. Enter freely and of your own will.

Harker steps over the threshold. Dracula smiles—very red lips, sharp white teeth.

COUNT DRACULA
I am Dracula. I bid you welcome, Mr. Harker.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA - DINING HALL - NIGHT

A long table, food laid for one. Dracula does not eat. He watches Harker with glittering eyes. Wolves howl far below.

COUNT DRACULA
Listen to them—the children of the night. What music they make.

Harker forces a smile, journal half-hidden. Candle flames lean as if in a draft though the air is still.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I am all in a sea of wonders. I dare not go out into the night.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA - HARKER'S ROOM - NIGHT

Harker tries the door—locked. He shaves by a small mirror. Dracula appears behind him in the room—yet the mirror shows no reflection but Harker’s own. Harker cuts himself. A bead of blood. Dracula’s eyes flash; he lunges toward the throat—then masters himself as the crucifix swings into view on Harker’s breast.

COUNT DRACULA
Take care how you cut yourself. It is more dangerous than you think in this country.

Dracula snatches the mirror and hurls it out the window. Glass shatters far below.

EXT. CASTLE DRACULA - RAMPARTS - NIGHT (MONTAGE)

Harker climbs in desperation along the outer wall. Below: the Count, lizard-like, crawls face-down the stone face of the castle in black cloak. Three pale women wait in a moonlit chamber—Harker later finds himself among them in a half-dream until Dracula hurls them back.

COUNT DRACULA
This man belongs to me!

Boxes of earth. The Count departing. Harker’s hair streaks with white at the temples. He drops from a window toward the abyss—

SMASH CUT TO:

EXT. EXETER RAILWAY STATION - DAY

Months later. PROFESSOR VAN HELSING, older, foreign, intense, stands at a carriage window with a bundle of papers. JONATHAN HARKER—older in the eyes, married now—sees him off. Van Helsing turns London papers in his hands. His eye catches the Westminster Gazette. He goes white.

VAN HELSING
Mein Gott! Mein Gott! So soon! so soon!

The whistle blows. The train moves. Van Helsing leans out.

VAN HELSING
Love to Madam Mina; I shall write so soon as ever I can.

INT. DR. SEWARD'S STUDY - ASYLUM - LATE AFTERNOON

DR. JOHN SEWARD at his desk. Order restored on the surface. VAN HELSING bounds in near half-past five and thrusts last night’s Westminster Gazette into Seward’s hand.

VAN HELSING
What do you think of that?

Seward scans a paragraph—children decoyed away at Hampstead—then small punctured wounds on their throats. He looks up.

DR. SEWARD
It is like poor Lucy’s.

VAN HELSING
And what do you make of it?

DR. SEWARD
Simply that there is some cause in common. Whatever it was that injured her has injured them.

VAN HELSING
That is true indirectly, but not directly.

DR. SEWARD
How do you mean, Professor?

Van Helsing’s face is sterner than in all their despair over Lucy.

VAN HELSING
Do you mean to tell me, friend John, that you have no suspicion as to what poor Lucy died of—not after all the hints given, not only by events, but by me?

DR. SEWARD
Of nervous prostration following on great loss or waste of blood.

VAN HELSING
And how the blood lost or waste?

Seward shakes his head. Van Helsing sits beside him.

VAN HELSING
You are clever man, friend John; you reason well, and your wit is bold; but you are too prejudiced. You do not let your eyes see nor your ears hear. Do you not think that there are things which you cannot understand, and yet which are? Ah, it is the fault of our science that it wants to explain all; and if it explain not, then it says there is nothing to explain.

He leans in.

VAN HELSING
Can you tell me why in the Pampas, ay and elsewhere, there are bats that come at night and open the veins of cattle and horses and suck dry their veins—and that when the sailors sleep on the deck, flit down on them, and then—in the morning are found dead men, white as even Miss Lucy was?

DR. SEWARD
Good God, Professor! Do you mean to tell me that Lucy was bitten by such a bat—and that such a thing is here in London in the nineteenth century?

Van Helsing waves for silence, eyes burning.

VAN HELSING
There are men and women who cannot die. We have to deal with one of them.

EXT. HAMPSTEAD HEATH / CHURCHYARD - NIGHT (BRIEF)

A pale figure in white—LUCY, bloated with undeath—lures a child among tombs. A glint of teeth. Then: stake, garlic, prayer—men’s hands end her true death. A look of peace settles on her face as the thing leaves her.

INT. SEWARD'S STUDY - NIGHT

Maps. Trains. Shipping. MINA HARKER—dark hair, steady courage—types and collates journals. JONATHAN, LORD GODALMING (ARTHUR), QUINCEY MORRIS (lean Texan with bowie), SEWARD, VAN HELSING gather around her work.

MINA HARKER
He came from Transylvania in boxes of earth. He must go back the same way if we force him from England.

VAN HELSING
We hunt the Un-Dead. We shall follow until the end.

EXT. VARNA / SEA / RIVER APPROACHES - DAY TO NIGHT (MONTAGE)

Steamers. Telegrams. The hunters close on a ship, then a river boat, then a leiter-wagon winding into snowy passes. Wolves call. Szgany gypsies guard a great wooden box on a cart. The Castle of Dracula stands distant against red sky.

EXT. MOUNTAIN ROAD NEAR CASTLE DRACULA - SUNSET

Snow. Long shadows. The cart with the box labours uphill. Szgany with knives and rifles ring it. Wolves howl behind the trees.

LORD GODALMING and DR. SEWARD level Winchesters, covering the circle. JONATHAN HARKER on one side, QUINCEY MORRIS on the other, force a way through the ring. Knives flash. Quincey parries with his great bowie; a blade catches his side—blood spurts through his fingers. He does not stop.

Jonathan leaps upon the cart. With incredible strength he raises the great box and flings it over the wheel to the ground. He drops beside it, Kukri out. Quincey staggers to the other end, bowie ready.

They prize the lid. Nails screech. The top flies back.

Inside: COUNT DRACULA lies upon his earth, deathly pale like a waxen image. Red eyes glare with horrible vindictive hate. The sinking sun touches the rim of the world. The look of hate turns toward triumph—

Jonathan’s Kukri sweeps. It shears through the throat. In the same instant Quincey’s bowie plunges into the heart.

Before their eyes the whole body crumbles into dust and passes from sight. On the face, in that final dissolution, a look of peace.

The Castle of Dracula stands out against the red sky; every stone of its broken battlements articulated in the setting sun.

The Szgany turn and flee. Wolves follow them. The hunters are left alone in the snow.

Quincey sinks to the ground, hand pressed to his side, blood still gushing. Mina flies to him—the holy circle no longer holding her back. Seward and Van Helsing kneel. Jonathan supports Quincey’s head on his shoulder. Quincey takes Mina’s hand with his clean one. He smiles.

QUINCEY MORRIS
I am only too happy to have been of any service! Oh, God—

He struggles up, pointing at Mina. The last red gleams bathe her face in rosy light. The men sink to their knees.

QUINCEY MORRIS
It was worth for this to die! Look! look! Now God be thanked that all has not been in vain! See! the snow is not more stainless than her forehead! The curse has passed away!

With a smile, in silence, he dies—a gallant gentleman.

A deep, earnest amen from the others.

EXT. CASTLE DRACULA - SUMMER DAY (YEARS LATER)

Seven years on. The castle still rears above a waste of desolation. No trace of the old horror remains in the stones.

EXT. ENGLISH GARDEN - DAY

JONATHAN and MINA with a small BOY on the grass. SEWARD and LORD GODALMING, both settled, nearby. VAN HELSING holds the boy on his knee. Papers—typed journals—lie in a tin box.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Seven years ago we all went through the flames; and the happiness of some of us since then is well worth the pain. It is an added joy to Mina and to me that our boy’s birthday is the same day as that on which Quincey Morris died. We call him Quincey.

VAN HELSING
We want no proofs; we ask none to believe us. This boy will some day know what a brave and gallant woman his mother is. Already he knows her sweetness and loving care; later on he will understand how some men so loved her, that they did dare much for her sake.

Mina’s forehead is clear in the sun. Jonathan’s hand rests on the closed journals.

FADE OUT.

THE END
